Otaku Hunter — Implementation Brief for Claude Code

**Project type:** New standalone game, separate repo from the existing Hanasou study app.
**Genre:** *Vampire Survivors*–style auto-battler (move-only input, auto-attack) with a Japanese-learning layer bolted onto the level-up screen.
**Engine:** Phaser 3 + Vite (web build, must run on **both** desktop and mobile in a browser; PWA-installable; leave room to wrap in Capacitor later).
**Content source:** Reuses the sentence data from Hanasou’s `lessons.js` (`window.LEVELS` + `window.LESSONS`). Do **not** rebuild the content — consume it.

This brief is the source of truth. Read the **Data Contract** section first; everything downstream depends on it.

-----

## 0. Build order (do it in this sequence)

1. Project scaffold (Phaser 3 + Vite, mobile+desktop input, one playable scene).
1. Data layer: load `lessons.js`, build the content index, write the **stage config** structure.
1. Core VS loop: movement, auto-attack, enemy spawner, XP, level-up trigger. **No learning yet** — use placeholder upgrade cards.
1. The particle-socket level-up minigame (the centerpiece — see §4). Wire it to grade-scale the upgrade.
1. Word pickups + Merch-Mule drops → run-only collected-word pool feeding the minigame.
1. Stages, bosses, character classes.
1. Polish: juice, SRS “haunting” requeue, persistence.

Get steps 1–4 working as a vertical slice before building breadth. The game must be *fun to survive* and *meaningful to level up* before stages/characters matter.

