## 5. Stages = curriculum (config-driven)

A stage is a plain config object. Adding content = adding a config + art, never touching core code.

```js
const STAGES = [
  {
    id: "arcade",
    name: "The Arcade",
    // content filter: which Hanasou content feeds this stage
    content: { levelIds: ["L1"], tiers: ["Beginner", "Intermediate"] }, // → resolves to themes → sentences
    tileset: "arcade",            // pixel bg + palette
    music: "...",
    enemyTable: ["RushFan","AnxiousOne","MerchMule","CameraGremlin"], // §6 keys + spawn weights
    spawnCurve: "...",            // density over time
    boss: "ultimate_collector",
    unlock: { requires: null },   // first stage, always unlocked
  },
  {
    id: "themepark",
    name: "The Theme Park",
    content: { levelIds: ["L3"], tiers: ["Getting around"] }, // travel/transaction content
    // ...
    unlock: { requires: "clear:arcade" },
  },
  // future: maid café, akihabara, station, comiket...
];
```

- `content` resolves through `LEVELS` → theme strings → `LESSONS.filter(section ∈ themes)` → that stage’s sentence + word pool.
- Stage unlock order should track `LEVELS` difficulty so progressing stages = advancing JLPT tiers. Unlocking a stage is the meta-progression carrot.

