## 8. Hard guardrails (write these into the code’s intent)

1. **The minigame must require knowing the Japanese, not pattern-matching.** Never show the JP answer during the puzzle (English/audio prompt only). Particle distractors must be from the real seen inventory. POS chip colors may be shown but must NOT be sufficient to solve — if a player can win by color-matching alone, the design has failed.
1. **No run-ending fail in the minigame.** It only scales rewards upward by degree. Wrong = smaller bonus, framed as bonus-missed, never as punishment.
1. **Combat is auto; learning is the level-up.** Do not turn moment-to-moment combat into a quiz. The contrast (frantic → calm think → frantic) is the design.
1. **Content is consumed, not authored.** All Japanese comes from `lessons.js`. Don’t hardcode sentences in the game.
1. **Both platforms, day one.** Every input and UI must work on touch (mobile) and mouse/keyboard (desktop). The minigame’s drag interactions especially.
1. **Stages and characters are data, not code.** New stage/character = new config object + assets.
1. **★ Content is plug-and-play and verification NEVER blocks it.** The game reads `lessons.js` directly and runs on whatever content is present, at any time, with zero pre-processing or validation step required. The audit/export tools in §11 are **read-only side tools** that observe the content — they are NOT a pipeline the content must pass through, NOT a gate, NOT a build dependency. Dropping in new/updated words or sentences must require nothing more than editing `lessons.js`. If a single entry is malformed, the game skips that one entry gracefully (per §4.4) and keeps running — one bad sentence never blocks the other 327.

