## 11. Content verification tools (STANDALONE — must never block the game)

These are two small **offline command-line scripts** that live in a `tools/` folder and run on demand. **Read this first:** they are read-only observers of `lessons.js`. They are NOT part of the build, NOT a pre-flight check, NOT something the game waits on. The game ships and runs whether or not these have ever been run. Their only job is to make human review cheap. Build them last (after the vertical slice), or skip until asked — they are not on the critical path.

The content-correctness strategy is: **machine catches mechanical errors → human (a fluent Japanese teacher) catches naturalness.** Don’t make the human proofread typos a script can find; don’t make a script judge naturalness it can’t.

### 11.1 `tools/audit-content.js` — offline JMdict mechanical check

A Node script that validates `lessons.js` against the **JMdict dictionary already bundled in Hanasou’s `vendor/`** (JMdict is the same dataset Jisho.org is built on — no network needed, and external dictionary APIs like jisho.org are not reliably reachable anyway). It:

1. Loads JMdict from `vendor/` (reuse Hanasou’s existing loader/format).
1. For every `words[]` entry across all lessons:
- **Existence:** does `w.jp` exist as a JMdict headword or reading? Flag if not found.
- **Gloss sanity:** does `w.en` overlap *any* JMdict sense gloss for that word? Flag if zero overlap (likely mistranslation). Skip this check for `pos:"prt"` and `pos:"expr"` (particles/set-phrases have grammatical glosses like `[topic]` that won’t match a dictionary).
- **POS agreement:** does `w.pos` roughly agree with JMdict’s POS? Flag clear disagreements (e.g. tagged `n` but JMdict only has it as a verb).
1. **Structural checks** (no dictionary needed): every sentence’s `words[]` concatenates to its `jp` (flag mismatches like `because#4`); romaji present; no empty fields; valid pos tags; every `lesson.section` maps to a `LEVELS` theme.
1. **Output:** a CSV/console report of ONLY the flagged items (`sid`, field, value, reason). A clean run prints “N sentences, M words, X flags.” It changes nothing and writes no game files.

This is a triage tool — expect a few dozen flags total, most being false positives on particles/expressions. Its purpose is to shrink what the human reviews, not to gate anything.

### 11.2 `tools/export-review-sheet.js` — human-review export

A Node script that dumps all content into a **flat, teacher-friendly review sheet** (CSV, openable in Excel/Sheets — or `.xlsx` if easy). One row per sentence:

|column                |source                                    |
|----------------------|------------------------------------------|
|`sid`                 |`${lessonId}#${index}`                    |
|`level / tier / theme`|resolved via LEVELS                       |
|`grammar point`       |`lesson.grammar`                          |
|English               |`sentence.en`                             |
|Japanese              |`sentence.jp`                             |
|Romaji                |`sentence.romaji`                         |
|Word breakdown        |`words[]` rendered as `jp(en)[pos]` joined|
|**Teacher notes**     |**empty column for corrections**          |
|**OK? (Y/N)**         |**empty column**                          |

The teacher reviews this sheet for the things no script can judge: **particle correctness in context, naturalness, register (casual vs polite), and translation nuance.** Corrections then flow back into `lessons.js` by hand (or via a small importer later if volume warrants). The teacher never touches source code.

### 11.3 The verification flow (for the README, so the human steps are clear)

```
build structure → confirm words plug in & game runs
        │  (game is fully functional from here — everything below is optional polish)
        ├─ run tools/audit-content.js   → clears mechanical errors (machine)
        ├─ run tools/export-review-sheet.js → hand sheet to fluent teacher (human)
        └─ fold corrections back into lessons.js → both apps pick them up automatically
```

Nothing in this flow is a prerequisite for shipping or playing. It runs whenever you want a content-quality pass, as many times as you want, on whatever content is in `lessons.js` at the time.